{"title_page": "Queen's Hospital", "text_new": "{{Short description|Hospital in Romford, London}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{about||the Queen's Hospital in Honolulu|The Queen's Medical Center|the hospital in New York City|Queens Hospital Center}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Queen's Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust]]\n| Image = Queens hospital london.jpg\n| Caption = <!-- optional -->\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5691|0.1789|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| Logo = <!-- optional -->\n| location = [[Romford]], [[London]], England, United Kingdom\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]]\n| Type = General\n| Speciality = \n| Helipad = Yes\n| Standards = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency = Yes\n| Affiliation = {{Plainlist|\n* [[American University of the Caribbean]]\n* [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n}}\n| Beds = 939\n| Founded = October 2006\n| Closed = <!-- optional -->\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type    = United Kingdom London Havering\t\n| map_caption = Shown in Havering\n|}}\n'''Queen's Hospital''' is a [[hospital]] in [[Romford]] in the [[London Borough of Havering]]. It was built on the site of the former Oldchurch Park, a short distance south of the town centre. It is run by [[Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:The_new_Oldchurch_Hospital,_Romford,_Essex_-_geograph.org.uk_-_26362.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The hospital under construction in 2005]]\nThe hospital was procured under a [[private finance initiative]] (PFI) contract to replace [[Harold Wood Hospital]], [[Oldchurch Hospital]], [[Rush Green Hospital]] and [[St George's Hospital, Havering]] in 2004. It was designed by Jonathan Bailey Associates and built by [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction|Bovis Lend Lease]] at a cost of \u00a3312 million  on Rom Valley Way, near the now demolished [[Romford Ice Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.healthcaredesignmagazine.com/architecture/queens-hospital-romford-essex-united-kingdom/|title=Queen's Hospital, Romford, Essex, United Kingdom|publisher=Healthcare Design|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://find-an-architect.architecture.com/ArchitectPractices/BDP/Projects/New-Romford-Hospital-60665.aspx|title=New Romford Hospital|publisher=RIBA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414010441/https://find-an-architect.architecture.com/ArchitectPractices/BDP/Projects/New-Romford-Hospital-60665.aspx|archive-date=14 April 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> Construction was completed in October 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's (Romford) Hospital, UK |url=https://www.hicl.com/queens-romford-hospital-uk |website=HICL Infrastructure |accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe hospital comprises four, circular, five-storey buildings, connected and surrounded by a wider two-storey building. The ground and first floor levels generally consist of diagnostic treatment, whilst the upper levels consist of inpatient services and wards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's Hospital 3D map |url=https://www.bhrhospitals.nhs.uk/download.cfm?doc=docm93jijm4n2233.pdf&ver=4412 |website=Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nIn July 2013 the [[Care Quality Commission]] issued a formal warning about the hospital, particularly for the accident and emergency department.<ref name=\"telegraph-20130710\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/10169934/AandE-patients-forced-to-wait-more-than-14-hours-at-struggling-hospital.html |title=A&E patients forced to wait more than 14 hours at struggling hospital |author=Richard Gray |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=10 July 2013 |accessdate=10 July 2013}}</ref> In March 2017,  after receiving a positive review from the care quality commission,  the hospital was taken out of special measures and praised by the commission for its work in a number of areas. <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.romfordrecorder.co.uk/news/health/queen-s-hospital-trust-out-of-special-measures-for-first-time-since-2013-after-positive-cqc-report-1-4919191|title=Queen's hospital trust out of special measures |author=Ralph Blackburn |newspaper= Romford Recorder |date = 7 March 2017| accessdate= 6 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Teaching ==\nThe hospital serves as a teaching hospital for medical students from the [[American University of the Caribbean]] and [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]].<ref>{{cite web |title=US and International Clinical Sites & Hospitals |url=https://www.aucmed.edu/academics/hospital-teaching-sites |website=American University of the Caribbean School of Medicine |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Key Facts - Medicine MBBS 5 Years (A100) - Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry |url=https://www.qmul.ac.uk/smd/undergraduate/courses/a100/ |website=Queen Mary University of London |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[London Buses]] routes 5, 103, 128, 174, 175, 193, 294, 365, 496, 498 and 499 serve the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bhrhospitals.nhs.uk/plan-your-journey|title=Planning your journey|publisher=Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref> The nearest railway station is [[Romford railway station|Romford]] on the [[Great Eastern Main Line]] and the nearest [[London Underground]] station is [[Elm Park tube station|Elm Park]] on the [[District line]].<ref>{{Citation step free tube map}}</ref>\n\n==Patient entertainment==\nThe hospital has an in-house hospital radio station operated by Bedrock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/PrintReport.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1094330&ReportType=COLOUR |title=Bedrock|publisher=Charity Commission|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> The service is free of charge to the in-patients. Bedrock previously served [[Oldchurch Hospital]] and [[Harold Wood Hospital]] until the new Queen's Hospital opened in 2006. [[Hospital Radio]] in [[Havering]] has been operating since 14 February 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedrockradio.org.uk/50years |title=Celebrating 50 years of Hospital Radio in Havering in 2014|publisher= Bedrock Radio |date=2 September 2013|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Healthcare in London]]\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/Services/Hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=RF4QH Queen's Hospital on the NHS website]\n* [https://www.cqc.org.uk/location/RF4QH Care Quality Commission inspection reports]\n\n{{Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2010}}\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 2006]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in London]]\n[[Category:Health in the London Borough of Havering]]\n[[Category:Romford]]\n[[Category:Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Hospital in Romford, London}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{about||the Queen's Hospital in Honolulu|The Queen's Medical Center|the hospital in New York City|Queens Hospital Center}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Queen's Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust]]\n| Image = Queens hospital london.jpg\n| Caption = <!-- optional -->\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5691|0.1789|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| Logo = <!-- optional -->\n| location = [[Romford]], [[London]], England, United Kingdom\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]]\n| Type = General\n| Speciality = \n| Helipad = Yes\n| Standards = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency = Yes\n| Affiliation = {{Plainlist|\n* [[American University of the Caribbean]]\n* [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n}}\n| Beds = 939\n| Founded = October 2006\n| Closed = <!-- optional -->\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type    = United Kingdom London Havering\t\n| map_caption = Shown in Havering\n|}}\n'''Queen's Hospital''' is a [[hospital]] in [[Romford]] in the [[London Borough of Havering]]. It was built on the site of the former Oldchurch Park, a short distance south of the town centre. It is run by [[Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:The_new_Oldchurch_Hospital,_Romford,_Essex_-_geograph.org.uk_-_26362.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The hospital under construction in 2005]]\nThe hospital was procured under a [[private finance initiative]] (PFI) contract to replace [[Harold Wood Hospital]], [[Oldchurch Hospital]], [[Rush Green Hospital]] and [[St George's Hospital, Havering]] in 2004. It was designed by Jonathan Bailey Associates and built by [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction|Bovis Lend Lease]] at a cost of \u00a3312 million  on Rom Valley Way, near the now demolished [[Romford Ice Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.healthcaredesignmagazine.com/architecture/queens-hospital-romford-essex-united-kingdom/|title=Queen's Hospital, Romford, Essex, United Kingdom|publisher=Healthcare Design|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://find-an-architect.architecture.com/ArchitectPractices/BDP/Projects/New-Romford-Hospital-60665.aspx|title=New Romford Hospital|publisher=RIBA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414010441/https://find-an-architect.architecture.com/ArchitectPractices/BDP/Projects/New-Romford-Hospital-60665.aspx|archive-date=14 April 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> Construction was completed in October 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's (Romford) Hospital, UK |url=https://www.hicl.com/queens-romford-hospital-uk |website=HICL Infrastructure |accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe hospital comprises four, circular, five-storey buildings, connected and surrounded by a wider two-storey building. The ground and first floor levels generally consist of diagnostic treatment, whilst the upper levels consist of inpatient services and wards. <ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's Hospital 3D map |url=https://www.bhrhospitals.nhs.uk/download.cfm?doc=docm93jijm4n2233.pdf&ver=4412 |website=Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nIn July 2013 the [[Care Quality Commission]] issued a formal warning about the hospital, particularly for the accident and emergency department.<ref name=\"telegraph-20130710\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/10169934/AandE-patients-forced-to-wait-more-than-14-hours-at-struggling-hospital.html |title=A&E patients forced to wait more than 14 hours at struggling hospital |author=Richard Gray |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=10 July 2013 |accessdate=10 July 2013}}</ref> In March 2017,  after receiving a positive review from the care quality commission,  the hospital was taken out of special measures and praised by the commission for its work in a number of areas. <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.romfordrecorder.co.uk/news/health/queen-s-hospital-trust-out-of-special-measures-for-first-time-since-2013-after-positive-cqc-report-1-4919191|title=Queen's hospital trust out of special measures |author=Ralph Blackburn |newspaper= Romford Recorder |date = 7 March 2017| accessdate= 6 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Teaching ==\nThe hospital serves as a teaching hospital for medical students from the [[American University of the Caribbean]] and [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]].<ref>{{cite web |title=US and International Clinical Sites & Hospitals |url=https://www.aucmed.edu/academics/hospital-teaching-sites |website=American University of the Caribbean School of Medicine |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Key Facts - Medicine MBBS 5 Years (A100) - Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry |url=https://www.qmul.ac.uk/smd/undergraduate/courses/a100/ |website=Queen Mary University of London |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[London Buses]] routes 5, 103, 128, 174, 175, 193, 294, 365, 496, 498 and 499 serve the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bhrhospitals.nhs.uk/plan-your-journey|title=Planning your journey|publisher=Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref> The nearest railway station is [[Romford railway station|Romford]] on the [[Great Eastern Main Line]] and the nearest [[London Underground]] station is [[Elm Park tube station|Elm Park]] on the [[District line]].<ref>{{Citation step free tube map}}</ref>\n\n==Patient entertainment==\nThe hospital has an in-house hospital radio station operated by Bedrock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/PrintReport.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1094330&ReportType=COLOUR |title=Bedrock|publisher=Charity Commission|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> The service is free of charge to the in-patients. Bedrock previously served [[Oldchurch Hospital]] and [[Harold Wood Hospital]] until the new Queen's Hospital opened in 2006. [[Hospital Radio]] in [[Havering]] has been operating since 14 February 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedrockradio.org.uk/50years |title=Celebrating 50 years of Hospital Radio in Havering in 2014|publisher= Bedrock Radio |date=2 September 2013|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Healthcare in London]]\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/