Team comparisons==\n[[File:Tyson Chandler (4).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Tyson Chandler]] was the only {{convert|7|ft|m|adj=on}} player on the 2012 team]]\nBryant and James  believed the 2012 team would win against the [[Dream Team (basketball)|Dream Team]], the 1992 Olympic team considered by some the greatest sports team ever assembled.<ref>{{cite news|title=This Day in Sports: The Dream Team Takes Gold in Barcelona |date=August 8, 2010 |work=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sportscenter/post/_/id/71610/this-day-in-sports-the-dream-team-takes-gold-in-barcelona |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vPDl23j?url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sportscenter/post/_/id/71610/this-day-in-sports-the-dream-team-takes-gold-in-barcelona |archivedate=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LeBron: We would beat Dream Team |date=July 28, 2012 |work=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/basketball/story/_/id/8205408/lebron-james-says-united-states-olympic-team-beat-1992-dream |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69nYQ0C0R?url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/basketball/story/_/id/8205408/lebron-james-says-united-states-olympic-team-beat-1992-dream |archivedate=August 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bryant said, \"[T]hey were a lot older, at kind of the end of their careers. We have just a bunch of young racehorses, guys that are eager to compete\".<ref name=espn20120712/> Dream Team member [[Charles Barkley]] said that he \"just started laughing\" upon hearing Bryant's comment and thought the 1992 team would win by double digits.<ref name=espn20120712>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/basketball/story/_/id/8158008/charles-barkley-says-1992-dream-team-beat-2012-olympic-team-double-digits|title=Charles Barkley fires back at Kobe|date=July 11, 2012|accessdate=July 12, 2012|work=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref> [[Michael Jordan]] added: \"For [Bryant] to compare those two teams is not one of the smarter things he ever could have done... Remember now, they learned from us. We didn't learn from them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/basketball/story/_/id/8159879/2012-olympics-michael-jordan-laughed-kobe-bryant-dream-team-boast|title=Michael Jordan: Dream Team better|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 12, 2012|work=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Jordan: Dream Team could take down this year's team|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/basketball/story/2012-07-12/michael-jordan-kobe-bryant-dream-team-olympics/56170692/1|publisher=USA Today|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref> Bird joked, \"They probably could. I haven't played in 20 years and we're all old now.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsgrid.com/nba/larry-bird-dream-team-kobe-response/|title=Larry Bird Is Also Laughing At Kobe Bryant Over His Dream Team Comments|date=July 12, 2012}}</ref> Bryant later clarified that he thought the 1992 team was better, but it was \"ludicrous\" to think his team could not beat the Dream Team in one game.<ref name=stein_magic>{{cite news|last=Stein |first=Marc |title=Magic Johnson lauds London squad |date=August 3, 2012 |work=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/basketball/story/_/id/8229564/london-olympics-1992-dream-teamers-laud-2012-team-efforts |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vQQj70z?url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/basketball/story/_/id/8229564/london-olympics-1992-dream-teamers-laud-2012-team-efforts |archivedate=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Erick |title=Kobe Bryant says Dream Team was better than '12 Olympic team |date=July 28, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/basketball/story/2012-07-28/kobe-bryant-clarifies-dream-team-better/56556032/1 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vQX6IX2?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/basketball/story/2012-07-28/kobe-bryant-clarifies-dream-team-better/56556032/1 |archivedate=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"You didn't ask me if we could beat them in a 7-game series\", he said.<ref>{{cite news|last=Golliver|first=Ben|title=Kobe Bryant on Michael Jordan's trash talk: 'He knows I'm a bad mother[expletive]'|date=July 13, 2012|work=CBSSports.com|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/eye-on-basketball/19574539/kobe-bryant-responds-to-michael-jordans-trash-talk-he-knows-im-a-bad-motherexpletive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214083626/http://www.cbssports.com/nba/eye-on-basketball/19574539/kobe-bryant-responds-to-michael-jordans-trash-talk-he-knows-im-a-bad-motherexpletive|archivedate=February 14, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMost experts believed the 1992 team would prevail with a distinct advantage with their centers, [[David Robinson (basketball)|David Robinson]] and [[Patrick Ewing]], over the smaller 2012 team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Turner |first=Broderick |title=Original 1992 Dream Team still the best |date=August 7, 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-dream-team-20120807,0,2437528.story |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vNXO6P2?url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-dream-team-20120807,0,2437528.story |archivedate=2012-08-15 |url-status=live |access-date=2012-08-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilbon |first=Michael |title=Dream Team set bar at Olympics |date=July 26, 2012 |work=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/story/_/id/8201633/2012-olympics-dream-team-legacy-set-bar-olympic-quality |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vMHFFXK?url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/story/_/id/8201633/2012-olympics-dream-team-legacy-set-bar-olympic-quality |archivedate=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Chandler was the only {{convert|7|ft|m|adj=on}} player on the 2012 team, but his offensive game was limited.<ref>{{cite news|last=Price |first=Greg |title=US Wins Gold Over Spain: So Are LeBron, Kobe, And Co. Better Than 1992 Dream Team? |date=August 12, 2012 |newspaper=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/372811/20120812/dream-team-kobe-bryant-lebron-james-michael.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69wx2jCvn?url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/372811/20120812/dream-team-kobe-bryant-lebron-james-michael.htm |archivedate=August 16, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some felt the discussion might have been more compelling if Dwight Howard and other injured big men were on the 2012 squad.<ref name=stein_magic/><ref>{{cite news|last=Simmons |first=Bill |title=The London Chronicles, Vol. 7: The Olympic Mega-Bag, Part 1 |date=August 13, 2012 |work=grantland.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8264283/olympic-mega-bag |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vNibJWg?url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8264283/olympic-mega-bag |archivedate=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Deveney |first=Sean |title=Olympics 2012: Comparing Team USA basketball to 2008 squad |date=July 28, 2012 |work=sportingnews.com |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/olympics/story/2012-07-28/olympics-2012-team-usa-basketball-past-results-compare-lebron-james-kobe-bryant |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69vNq9s39?url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/olympics/story/2012-07-28/olympics-2012-team-usa-basketball-past-results-compare-lebron-james-kobe-bryant |archivedate=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> NBA coach [[Doc Rivers]] felt the London team had an advantage with their outside shooting over the Dream Team.<ref name=amick/> Like Barkley, [[CBSSports.com]] opined that only three members of the 2012 team\u2014Bryant, James, and Durant\u2014would have made the Dream Team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Golliver|first=Ben|title=Michael Jordan, Charles Barkley to Kobe Bryant: Dream Team better than 2012 squad|date=July 12, 2012|work=CBSSports.com|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/eye-on-basketball/19571318/michael-jordan-charles-barkley-tell-kobe-bryant-dream-team-was-better-than-2012-squad|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214081540/http://www.cbssports.com/nba/eye-on-basketball/19571318/michael-jordan-charles-barkley-tell-kobe-bryant-dream-team-was-better-than-2012-squad|archivedate=December 14, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Dream Team averaged 117.3 points and won its games by an average of 43.8 points. The 2012 team averaged a similar point total (115.5) but won by a lesser margin (32.1). The Dream Team beat [[Croatia national basketball team|Croatia]] by 32 in the gold-medal game, while the 2012 team won by just seven. However, the level of international competition improved since 1992.<ref name=amick>{{cite news|last=Amick |first=Sam |title=Jordan: Dream Team would have no problem vs. London gold medalists |date=August 15, 2012 |work=SI.com |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/sam_amick/08/15/michael-jordan/index.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69wxpn5fO?url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/sam_amick/08/15/michael-jordan/index.html |archivedate=August 16, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Levin |first=Josh |title=What's the Difference Between the 1992 and 2012 Dream Teams? Kevin Durant and LeBron James Played Tougher Competition. |date=August 12, 2012 |magazine=Slate |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/five_ring_circus/2012/08/12/_2012_u_s_olympic_basketball_team_the_original_dream_team_was_great_but_lebron_james_and_kevin_durant_played_tougher_competition_.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69wxzZB0e?url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/five_ring_circus/2012/08/12/_2012_u_s_olympic_basketball_team_the_original_dream_team_was_great_but_lebron_james_and_kevin_durant_played_tougher_competition_.html |archivedate=August 16, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The 2012 team faced a tougher opponent in Spain, which had seven NBA players; Croatia in 1992 had only two NBA players at that point.<ref name=diamond/> Overall, the 2012 Olympic field had 39 NBA players and 18 former NBA players were on team rosters, while rosters in 1992 had 17 NBA players and three other former players\u2014more than half of those NBA players were on the Dream Team.<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Zillgitt \n |first=Jeff \n |title=USA men survive Spain to win basketball gold medal \n |date=August 12, 2012 \n |newspaper=USA Today \n |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/basketball/story/2012-08-12/usa-gold-medal-game-spain/57009558/1?loc=interstitialskip \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69wcpjwU5?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/basketball/story/2012-08-12/usa-gold-medal-game-spain/57009558/1?loc=interstitialskip \n |archivedate=August 15, 2012 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n;General\n*{{cite news |title=USA Combined Team Statistics (as of Aug 12, 2012) |work=usabasketball.com |url=http://www.usabasketball.com/misc/12_moly_stats_usa.pdf |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69tnSJGCi?url=http://www.usabasketball.com/misc/12_moly_stats_usa.pdf |archivedate=August 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all |access-date=August 14, 2012 }}\n\n;Specific\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|United States men's national basketball team at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 United States men's Olympic basketball team}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140903135856/http://archive.usab.com/mens/national/12_moly_results.html 2012 Men's Olympic Basketball Competition Results] at usabasketball.com\n\n{{United States men's national basketball team}}\n{{United States Men Basketball Squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament}}\n{{Summer Olympics basketball tournament winners}}\n\n[[Category:United States at the Olympic Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n[[Category:Countries at the 2012 Olympic Men's Basketball Tournament|United States]]\n[[Category:2012\u201313 in American basketball|Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "NBA. Corrector", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eRoster:Fixed misconception)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_United_States_men%27s_Olympic_basketball_team"}
{"title_page": "Trolls World Tour", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 animated film directed by Walt Dohrn}}\n{{Redirect|Trolls 2|the 1990 horror film|Troll 2}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Trolls World Tour\n| image          = Trolls_World_Tour_poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Original poster with release date\n| director       = [[Walt Dohrn]]\n| producer       = [[Gina Shay]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel<br>Glenn Berger]]\n* Elizabeth Tippet\n* [[Maya Forbes]]\n* [[Wallace Wolodarsky]]\n}}\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* Jonathan Aibel\n* Glenn Berger\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Troll doll]]s|[[Thomas Dam]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anna Kendrick]]\n* [[Justin Timberlake]]\n* [[James Corden]]\n* [[Kunal Nayyar]]\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n* [[Rachel Bloom]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Theodore Shapiro]]<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\">{{cite news |last1=Sarto |first1=Dan |title=DreamWorks Animation Reveals 21 Posters and Cast for \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 |url= https://dazntvstreams.com/movies/ |work=Animation World Network |date=19 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Nick Fletcher]]\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|04|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 91 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90 million<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/as-a-virus-upends-hollywood-may-never-be-a-return-normal-1286691 | last1=Keegan | first1=Rebecca | title=As a Virus Upends Hollywood, There May Never Be a Return to Normal | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 26, 2020 | accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $1.9 million<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1535018497/ | title=Trolls World Tour (2020) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Trolls World Tour''''' (titled as '''''Trolls 2: World Tour''''' from release) is a 2020 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[jukebox musical]] film produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film is a [[sequel]] to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', directed by [[Walt Dohrn]] with co-direction by David P. Smith, produced by [[Gina Shay]], and written by [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel, Glenn Berger]], Elizabeth Tippet, [[Maya Forbes]] and [[Wallace Wolodarsky]], from a story by Aibel and Berger. The film stars [[Anna Kendrick]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[James Corden]], [[Kunal Nayyar]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], and [[Rachel Bloom]].\n\n''Trolls World Tour'' was set to be theatrically released in the United States on April 10, 2020. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the film will instead be released on [[video on demand|digital rental]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nAfter the events of the [[Trolls (film)|first film]], Poppy and Branch discover that there are other different kinds of Trolls scattered over six different lands, each devoted to a different form of music: [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Funk]], [[Classical music|Classical]], [[Techno music|Techno]], [[Country music|Country]], and [[Rock music|Rock]]. Their world is about to get a lot bigger, and a whole lot louder, as member of hard-rock royalty, Queen Barb, aided by her father King Thrash, wants to destroy all other kinds of music to let rock reign supreme. With the fate of the world at stake, Poppy and Branch, along with their friends \u2014 Smidge, Legsly, Biggie, Satin and Chenille, Cooper, Guy Diamond and Tiny Diamond \u2014 set out to visit all the other lands to unify the Trolls in harmony against Barb, who's looking to upstage them all and turn them into rock zombies.<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\" /> Meanwhile, Branch tries to find a way to tell Poppy how he feels about her.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anna Kendrick]] as Queen Poppy, the sweetest, optimistic Queen of the pop Trolls and Branch's girlfriend and love interest.\n* [[Justin Timberlake]] as Branch, an over-cautious, good-hearted survivalist pop Troll and Poppy's boyfriend and love interest.\n* [[James Corden]] as Biggie, a chubby, friendly pop Troll.\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] as King Thrash, former King of the Hard Rock Trolls and Barb's father.\n* [[Rachel Bloom]] as Queen Barb, the Queen of the Hard Rock Trolls and Thrash's daughter.\n* [[Anderson Paak]] as Prince D, a Funk Troll and Quincy and Essence's son.\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] as King Quincy, the King of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Mary J. Blige]] as Queen Essence, the Queen of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]] as Delta Dawn, the half-troll half-sheep leader of the Country Trolls.\n* [[Sam Rockwell]] as Hickory, a Yodel Troll who is disguised as a Country Troll.\n* [[Icona Pop]] as Satin and Chenille, fashion Troll twins who are conjoined at their hairs.\n* [[Ron Funches]] as Cooper, a giraffe-like troll who walks on all fours.\n* [[Kunal Nayyar]] as Guy Diamond, a glittery, silver naked pop Troll with a highly auto-tuned voice.\n* [[Jamie Dornan]] as Chaz, a Smooth Jazz Troll.\n* [[J Balvin]] as Tresillo, the leader of the Reggaeton Trolls.\n* [[Kenan Thompson]] as Tiny Diamond, a Hip-Hop Troll and Guy Diamond's newborn son.\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Mr. Dinkles, Biggie's pet worm.\n* [[Walt Dohrn]] as \n** Smidge, a small female pop Troll with a masculine voice.\n** Cloud Guy, an anthropomorphic cloud\n** King Peppy, Poppy's father and the former King of the pop Trolls. He was previously voiced by [[Jeffrey Tambor]].\n** Fuzzbert, a hair pop troll with legs\n** Additional voices\n* [[Ester Dean]] as Legsly, a Pop Troll.\n* [[Gustavo Dudamel]] as Trollzart, a Classical Troll.\n* [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]] as King Trollex, the King of the Techno Trolls.\n* [[Flula Borg]] as Dickory, a Yodel Troll who is inside of the back of Hickory\n* [[Charlyne Yi]] as Pennywhistle, a whistle\n* The McElroy Brothers as Skyscraper\n** [[Justin McElroy]] as Techno Beat Drop Button, Tumbleweed\n** [[Travis McElroy]] as Rock Tear\n** [[Griffin McElroy]] as Country Tear\n* [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]] as the K-Pop Gang:<ref name=BillboardTrolls2020>{{cite news|title=Red Velvet Share Troll-ish Character Posters for 'Trolls World Tour'|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/international/8550504/red-velvet-share-troll-ish-character-posters-for-trolls-world|work=Billboard|date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Wendy]] voices Wani, the leader of the K-Pop Trolls and Tresillo\u2019s rival.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Irene]] voices Baby Bun, Wani\u2019s lieutenant.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Seulgi]] voices Gomdori, Wani\u2019s third in command.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Joy]] voices Ari, the most silent of the K-Pop Trolls.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Yeri]] voices Kim-Petit, Gomdori\u2019s best friend.\n\n==Production==\nOn February 28, 2017, [[Universal Pictures]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]] announced a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', with [[Anna Kendrick]] and [[Justin Timberlake]] reprising their roles as Poppy and Branch.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Universal DreamWorks Animation Announces \u2018Trolls 2\u2019; Sets for April 10, 2020|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/trolls-2-announced-april-2020-dreamworks-animation-1201998983/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Variety|date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, podcasters the [[My Brother, My Brother and Me|McElroy brothers]] began campaigning for roles in the film via a podcast titled \"The McElroy Brothers Will Be in Trolls 2\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maximumfun.org/my-brother-my-brother-and-me/mcelroy-brothers-will-be-trolls-2-chapter-1|title=The McElroy Brothers Will Be In Trolls 2: Chapter 1 {{!}} Maximum Fun|website=www.maximumfun.org|language=en|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref> Following the campaign's success, DreamWorks confirmed in September 2018 that the McElroy brothers would make cameo appearances in ''World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/09/trolls-world-tour-mcelroy-brothers-casting |title=The Unbelievable True Story of How Three Podcasters Trolled Their Way into Trolls 2 |last=Bradley |first=Laura |date=September 11, 2018 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Sam Rockwell]], [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]], [[Jamie Dornan]] and [[Flula Borg]] were added to the cast in May 2018. Corden, Stefani, Icona Pop, Funches, and Nayyar returned to reprise their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chance-rapper-joins-cast-trolls-2-1110763|title=Chance the Rapper Joins the Cast of 'Trolls 2'|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> On June 12, 2018, the film was retitled as ''Trolls World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/features/new-details-revealed-about-dreamworks-trolls-sequel/|title=New Details Revealed About DreamWorks\u2019 \u2018Trolls\u2019 Sequel|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/laverne-cox-disclosure-trans-lives-on-screen-documentary-1202843851/|title=Film News Roundup: Laverne Cox Boards 'Disclosure: Trans Lives on Screen' Documentary|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|first2=Dave|last2=McNary|date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, it was confirmed that [[Kelly Clarkson]] had joined the cast, and will perform an original song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/kelly-clarkson-trolls-2-perform-original-song-1202476507/|title=Kelly Clarkson Joins \u2018Trolls 2\u2019 & Will Perform Original Song|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, along with promotional posters, new cast members have been announced, which include: [[J Balvin]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Rachel Bloom]], [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], [[Ester Dean]] and [[Gustavo Dudamel]].<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\"/>\n\nAlong with Timberlake, Clarkson, Paak, Blige and Clinton, songs are provided by [[Chris Stapleton]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]].\n\nThe first single from the movie's soundtrack, \"[[The Other Side (SZA and Justin Timberlake song)|The Other Side]]\", by Timberlake and SZA, was released on February 26, 2020. The ''[[Trolls World Tour (soundtrack)|Trolls World Tour: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' was released on March 13, 2020.\n\n==Release==\n[[Universal Pictures]] originally planned to release ''Trolls World Tour'' theatrically in the United States on April 10, 2020.<ref name=Trolls2DateChange>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/fast-furious-9-easter-weekend-2020-release-date-trolls-2-valentines-day-opening-2020-1202181866/|title=\u2018Fast & Furious 9\u2019 Drives To Easter Weekend 2020; \u2018Trolls 2\u2019 Moves To Spring 2020 \u2013 Update|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> It was later pushed up to February 14, 2020 before being moved to April 17, 2020. Following the delay of ''[[No Time to Die]]'', it was once again pushed up to the original April 10 release date.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/trolls-world-tour-opening-easter-no-time-to-die-coronavirus-release-date-change-1202874398/|title=\u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Fills Easter Void Left By \u2018No Time To Die\u2019|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2020-03-04|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> It was also set to be released on March 20 in the United Kingdom, but due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], its release date was pushed back to April 10. \n\nOn March 16, Universal announced that the film would be released in theaters and for rental on digital platforms simultaneously on April 10.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuster |first1=Jeremy |title=Universal to Release 'Trolls World Tour' for Digital Rental on Same Day as Theatrical Release |url=https://www.thewrap.com/universal-to-release-trolls-world-tour-for-digital-rental-on-same-day-as-theatrical-release/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> However, recent social media posts for the film confirm that its theatrical release has been scrapped, and it will instead be released digitally on the intended date.\n\n===Marketing===\nOn June 19, 2019, DreamWorks released 22 character posters for the film, along with promotional film stills.<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\" /> On June 20, the first trailer was released.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yP86-TR6IME</ref>\n\nA second trailer was released in November 14, 2019. A third trailer was released on March 6, 2020, featuring the new release date.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.dreamworks.com/movies/trolls-world-tour}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt6587640}}\n\n{{Trolls}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Trolls (film)]]\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2020s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:2020s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about trolls]]\n[[Category:Films based on toys]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musical films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Theodore Shapiro]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 animated film directed by Walt Dohrn}}\n{{Redirect|Trolls 2|the 1990 horror film|Troll 2}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Trolls World Tour\n| image          = Trolls_World_Tour_poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Original poster with release date\n| director       = [[Walt Dohrn]]\n| producer       = [[Gina Shay]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel<br>Glenn Berger]]\n* Elizabeth Tippet\n* [[Maya Forbes]]\n* [[Wallace Wolodarsky]]\n}}\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* Jonathan Aibel\n* Glenn Berger\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Troll doll]]s|[[Thomas Dam]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anna Kendrick]]\n* [[Justin Timberlake]]\n* [[James Corden]]\n* [[Kunal Nayyar]]\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n* [[Rachel Bloom]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Theodore Shapiro]]<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\">{{cite news |last1=Sarto |first1=Dan |title=DreamWorks Animation Reveals 21 Posters and Cast for \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 |url= https://dazntvstreams.com/movies/ |work=Animation World Network |date=19 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Nick Fletcher]]\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|04|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 91 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90 million<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/as-a-virus-upends-hollywood-may-never-be-a-return-normal-1286691 | last1=Keegan | first1=Rebecca | title=As a Virus Upends Hollywood, There May Never Be a Return to Normal | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 26, 2020 | accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $1.9 million<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1535018497/ | title=Trolls World Tour (2020) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Trolls World Tour''''' (titled as '''''Trolls 2: World Tour''''' from release) is a 2020 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[jukebox musical]] film produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment]]. The film is a [[sequel]] to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', directed by [[Walt Dohrn]] with co-direction by David P. Smith, produced by [[Gina Shay]], and written by [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel, Glenn Berger]], Elizabeth Tippet, [[Maya Forbes]] and [[Wallace Wolodarsky]], from a story by Aibel and Berger. The film stars [[Anna Kendrick]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[James Corden]], [[Kunal Nayyar]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], and [[Rachel Bloom]].\n\n''Trolls World Tour'' was set to be theatrically released in the United States on April 10, 2020. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the film will instead be released on [[video on demand|digital rental]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nAfter the events of the [[Trolls (film)|first film]], Poppy and Branch discover that there are other different kinds of Trolls scattered over six different lands, each devoted to a different form of music: [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Funk]], [[Classical music|Classical]], [[Techno music|Techno]], [[Country music|Country]], and [[Rock music|Rock]]. Their world is about to get a lot bigger, and a whole lot louder, as member of hard-rock royalty, Queen Barb, aided by her father King Thrash, wants to destroy all other kinds of music to let rock reign supreme. With the fate of the world at stake, Poppy and Branch, along with their friends \u2014 Smidge, Legsly, Biggie, Satin and Chenille, Cooper, Guy Diamond and Tiny Diamond \u2014 set out to visit all the other lands to unify the Trolls in harmony against Barb, who's looking to upstage them all and turn them into rock zombies.<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\" /> Meanwhile, Branch tries to find a way to tell Poppy how he feels about her.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anna Kendrick]] as Queen Poppy, the sweetest, optimistic Queen of the pop Trolls and Branch's girlfriend and love interest.\n* [[Justin Timberlake]] as Branch, an over-cautious, good-hearted survivalist pop Troll and Poppy's boyfriend and love interest.\n* [[James Corden]] as Biggie, a chubby, friendly pop Troll.\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] as King Thrash, former King of the Hard Rock Trolls and Barb's father.\n* [[Rachel Bloom]] as Queen Barb, the Queen of the Hard Rock Trolls and Thrash's daughter.\n* [[Anderson Paak]] as Prince D, a Funk Troll and Quincy and Essence's son.\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] as King Quincy, the King of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Mary J. Blige]] as Queen Essence, the Queen of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]] as Delta Dawn, the half-troll half-sheep leader of the Country Trolls.\n* [[Sam Rockwell]] as Hickory, a Yodel Troll who is disguised as a Country Troll.\n* [[Icona Pop]] as Satin and Chenille, fashion Troll twins who are conjoined at their hairs.\n* [[Ron Funches]] as Cooper, a giraffe-like troll who walks on all fours.\n* [[Kunal Nayyar]] as Guy Diamond, a glittery, silver naked pop Troll with a highly auto-tuned voice.\n* [[Jamie Dornan]] as Chaz, a Smooth Jazz Troll.\n* [[J Balvin]] as Tresillo, the leader of the Reggaeton Trolls.\n* [[Kenan Thompson]] as Tiny Diamond, a Hip-Hop Troll and Guy Diamond's newborn son.\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Mr. Dinkles, Biggie's pet worm.\n* [[Walt Dohrn]] as \n** Smidge, a small female pop Troll with a masculine voice.\n** Cloud Guy, an anthropomorphic cloud\n** King Peppy, Poppy's father and the former King of the pop Trolls. He was previously voiced by [[Jeffrey Tambor]].\n** Fuzzbert, a hair pop troll with legs\n** Additional voices\n* [[Ester Dean]] as Legsly, a Pop Troll.\n* [[Gustavo Dudamel]] as Trollzart, a Classical Troll.\n* [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]] as King Trollex, the King of the Techno Trolls.\n* [[Flula Borg]] as Dickory, a Yodel Troll who is inside of the back of Hickory\n* [[Charlyne Yi]] as Pennywhistle, a whistle\n* The McElroy Brothers as Skyscraper\n** [[Justin McElroy]] as Techno Beat Drop Button, Tumbleweed\n** [[Travis McElroy]] as Rock Tear\n** [[Griffin McElroy]] as Country Tear\n* [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]] as the K-Pop Gang:<ref name=BillboardTrolls2020>{{cite news|title=Red Velvet Share Troll-ish Character Posters for 'Trolls World Tour'|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/international/8550504/red-velvet-share-troll-ish-character-posters-for-trolls-world|work=Billboard|date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Wendy]] voices Wani, the leader of the K-Pop Trolls and Tresillo\u2019s rival.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Irene]] voices Baby Bun, Wani\u2019s lieutenant.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Seulgi]] voices Gomdori, Wani\u2019s third in command.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Joy]] voices Ari, the most silent of the K-Pop Trolls.\n** [[Red Velvet (group)|Yeri]] voices Kim-Petit, Gomdori\u2019s best friend.\n\n==Production==\nOn February 28, 2017, [[Universal Pictures]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]] announced a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', with [[Anna Kendrick]] and [[Justin Timberlake]] reprising their roles as Poppy and Branch.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Universal DreamWorks Animation Announces \u2018Trolls 2\u2019; Sets for April 10, 2020|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/trolls-2-announced-april-2020-dreamworks-animation-1201998983/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Variety|date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, podcasters the [[My Brother, My Brother and Me|McElroy brothers]] began campaigning for roles in the film via a podcast titled \"The McElroy Brothers Will Be in Trolls 2\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maximumfun.org/my-brother-my-brother-and-me/mcelroy-brothers-will-be-trolls-2-chapter-1|title=The McElroy Brothers Will Be In Trolls 2: Chapter 1 {{!}} Maximum Fun|website=www.maximumfun.org|language=en|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref> Following the campaign's success, DreamWorks confirmed in September 2018 that the McElroy brothers would make cameo appearances in ''World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/09/trolls-world-tour-mcelroy-brothers-casting |title=The Unbelievable True Story of How Three Podcasters Trolled Their Way into Trolls 2 |last=Bradley |first=Laura |date=September 11, 2018 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Sam Rockwell]], [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]], [[Jamie Dornan]] and [[Flula Borg]] were added to the cast in May 2018. Corden, Stefani, Icona Pop, Funches, and Nayyar returned to reprise their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chance-rapper-joins-cast-trolls-2-1110763|title=Chance the Rapper Joins the Cast of 'Trolls 2'|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> On June 12, 2018, the film was retitled as ''Trolls World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/features/new-details-revealed-about-dreamworks-trolls-sequel/|title=New Details Revealed About DreamWorks\u2019 \u2018Trolls\u2019 Sequel|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/laverne-cox-disclosure-trans-lives-on-screen-documentary-1202843851/|title=Film News Roundup: Laverne Cox Boards 'Disclosure: Trans Lives on Screen' Documentary|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|first2=Dave|last2=McNary|date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, it was confirmed that [[Kelly Clarkson]] had joined the cast, and will perform an original song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/kelly-clarkson-trolls-2-perform-original-song-1202476507/|title=Kelly Clarkson Joins \u2018Trolls 2\u2019 & Will Perform Original Song|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, along with promotional posters, new cast members have been announced, which include: [[J Balvin]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Rachel Bloom]], [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], [[Ester Dean]] and [[Gustavo Dudamel]].<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\"/>\n\nAlong with Timberlake, Clarkson, Paak, Blige and Clinton, songs are provided by [[Chris Stapleton]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]].\n\nThe first single from the movie's soundtrack, \"[[The Other Side (SZA and Justin Timberlake song)|The Other Side]]\", by Timberlake and SZA, was released on February 26, 2020. The ''[[Trolls World Tour (soundtrack)|Trolls World Tour: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' was released on March 13, 2020.\n\n==Release==\n[[Universal Pictures]] originally planned to release ''Trolls World Tour'' theatrically in the United States on April 10, 2020.<ref name=Trolls2DateChange>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/fast-furious-9-easter-weekend-2020-release-date-trolls-2-valentines-day-opening-2020-1202181866/|title=\u2018Fast & Furious 9\u2019 Drives To Easter Weekend 2020; \u2018Trolls 2\u2019 Moves To Spring 2020 \u2013 Update|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> It was later pushed up to February 14, 2020 before being moved to April 17, 2020. Following the delay of ''[[No Time to Die]]'', it was once again pushed up to the original April 10 release date.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/trolls-world-tour-opening-easter-no-time-to-die-coronavirus-release-date-change-1202874398/|title=\u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Fills Easter Void Left By \u2018No Time To Die\u2019|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2020-03-04|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> It was also set to be released on March 20 in the United Kingdom, but due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], its release date was pushed back to April 10. \n\nOn March 16, Universal announced that the film would be released in theaters and for rental on digital platforms simultaneously on April 10.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuster |first1=Jeremy |title=Universal to Release 'Trolls World Tour' for Digital Rental on Same Day as Theatrical Release |url=https://www.thewrap.com/universal-to-release-trolls-world-tour-for-digital-rental-on-same-day-as-theatrical-release/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> However, recent social media posts for the film confirm that its theatrical release has been scrapped, and it will instead be released digitally on the intended date.\n\n===Marketing===\nOn June 19, 2019, DreamWorks released 22 character posters for the film, along with promotional film stills.<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\" /> On June 20, the first trailer was released.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yP86-TR6IME</ref>\n\nA second trailer was released in November 14, 2019. A third trailer was released on March 6, 2020, featuring the new release date.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.dreamworks.com/movies/trolls-world-tour}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt6587640}}\n\n{{Trolls}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Trolls (film)]]\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category: