{"title_page": "Malvina Major", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Dame Malvina Major \n| honorific_suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZ|GNZMf|DBE|size=100%}}\n| image               = Malvina Major (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = Major in 2016\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Malvina Lorraine Major\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1943|1|28}}\n| death_date          =\n| origin              = [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], New Zealand\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Classical music|Classical]]|[[Opera (Music)|opera]]}}\n| occupation          = Singer, teacher\n| years_active        = 1965\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             =\n}}\n'''Dame Malvina Lorraine Major''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZ|GNZMf|DBE}} (born 28 January 1943) is a New Zealand opera singer.\n\n==Early life==\nMajor was born in [[Hamilton, New Zealand]] into a large musical family. As a child she performed at various concerts, singing mainly [[Country music|country and western]] pop and music from the shows. She received her first classical training in 1955, from Sister Mary Magdalen at [[Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia]], north of Hamilton. Sister Febronie continued with her voice training and Sister Liguori gave her piano tuition. As her potential blossomed, Major began travelling weekly to [[Ponsonby, New Zealand|Ponsonby]] in [[Auckland]], where she received further tuition from [[Sister Mary Leo|Dame Sister Mary Leo]] at St Mary's College Music School.  Sister Mary Leo was internationally recognised as one of the great music teachers, and she later taught another famous New Zealand soprano, Dame [[Kiri Te Kanawa]].\n\n==International recognition==\n\nMajor later moved to England for further study at the London Opera Centre under the guidance of teacher [[Ruth Packer]]. Her successes include winning the 1963 [[Mobil Song Quest|New Zealand Mobil Song Quest]] beating Te Kanawa who placed second (Te Kanawa later won the 1965 contest). She also won the Australian [[Melbourne Sun-Aria]] in 1965, and the London-based [[Kathleen Ferrier Award]] in 1966. Major later performed in international concerts including a [[BBC]] concert broadcast in London, an outdoor concert at the [[Egyptian pyramids|pyramids]] in Egypt with the [[Cairo Opera House|Cairo Symphony Orchestra]], and a charity concert for [[Vera Lynn]] in London. She has performed more than 30 opera roles in their original languages.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nMajor was made a [[Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE)<ref>{{cite web|title=KNIGHTS AND DAMES OF THE ORDERS OF CHIVALRY|url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/nzom3|work=New Zealand Honours Lists|publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet|accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref> in 1991 in recognition of her contributions to music, and a Principal Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit (PCNZM) in the [[2008 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2008 New Year Honours]] for services to opera.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/new-year-honours-list-2008 | title=New Year honours list 2008 |date=31 December 2007 | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet | accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> This was later exchanged for Dame Grand Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/list.asp?id=46 | title=New Zealand Honours Lists | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |year=2008 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Major received the [[Benny Award]] from the [[Variety Artists Club of New Zealand|Variety Artists Club of New Zealand Inc]].\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vacnz.com/bennyaward/|title=Variety Artists Club of NZ Benny Award Recipients|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016033941/http://www.vacnz.com/bennyaward/|archivedate=16 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2008, Major performed a solo and duet with [[Hayley Westenra]] on the ChristChurch Cathedral Choir 2008 UK Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christchurchcathedralchoir.com/ | title=ChristChurch Cathedral Choir 2008 UK Tour | publisher=christchurchcathedralchoir.com |year=2008 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/266275/ART-BEAT | title=With passion | publisher=stuff.co.nz |date=13 February 2008 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> On 18 March 2011, Major performed in the national Christchurch memorial service at [[Hagley Park, Christchurch|Hagley Park]] of [[Christchurch]] in the presence of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]], Prime Minister [[John Key]], [[Bob Parker (mayor)|Bob Parker]], Hayley Westenra, [[ChristChurch Cathedral, Christchurch|ChristChurch Cathedral]] Choir, dignitaries, international rescue teams and tens of thousands of [[New Zealanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/christchurch-memorial-music-performers-march-18-19-29-video-4072141/video | title=Christchurch memorial music performers | publisher=dpmc.govt.nz |date=18 March 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> On 25 February 2012, Major performed with soprano Amina Edris and tenor Chase Douglas in the Waikato Times Hamilton Gardens Arts Festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamiltongardensartsfestival.co.nz/performers/234-1-Countertenors-The-Voice-of-an-Angel |title=Dame Malvina Major \u2013 Coming Home |publisher=dpmc.govt.nz |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/6119956/Dame-Malvina-top-act-for-festival |title=Dame Malvina top act for festival |publisher=stuff.co.nz |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|2012 Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee Honours]], Major was appointed to the [[Order of New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee Honours List 2012 |url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/node/1045 |work=New Zealand Honours Lists |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=29 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604202359/http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/node/1045 |archivedate=4 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This is the highest honour awarded by the Queen of New Zealand, and entitles members of use the post-nominal letters ONZ.\n\n==Education==\n\nMajor is currently{{when|date=August 2015}} Professor of Voice at the [[University of Waikato]] in [[Hamilton, New Zealand]].\n\nIn 1992 she established a foundation to promote education through awards and provide training for young New Zealanders in the performing arts. One such recipient of her personal training is Hayley Westenra.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*  Official website http://www.damemalvinamajorfoundation.org/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Order of New Zealand}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Major, Malvina}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Dames Grand Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Singers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female singers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand music teachers]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand singers]]\n[[Category:Women music educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women opera singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Dame Malvina Major \n| honorific_suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZ|GNZMf|DBE|size=100%}}\n| image               = Malvina Major (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = Major in 2016\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Malvina Lorraine Major\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1943|1|28}}\n| death_date          =\n| origin              = [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], New Zealand\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Classical music|Classical]]|[[Opera (Music)|opera]]}}\n| occupation          = Singer, teacher\n| years_active        = 1965\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             =\n}}\n'''Dame Malvina Lorraine Major''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZ|GNZMf|DBE}} (born 28 January 1943) is a New Zealand opera singer.\n\n==Early life==\nMajor was born in [[Hamilton, New Zealand]] into a large musical family. As a child she performed at various concerts, singing mainly [[Country music|country and western]] pop and music from the shows. She received her first classical training in 1955, from Sister Mary Magdalen at [[Ngaruawahia]], north of Hamilton. Sister Febronie continued with her voice training and Sister Liguori gave her piano tuition. As her potential blossomed, Major began travelling weekly to [[Ponsonby, New Zealand|Ponsonby]] in [[Auckland]], where she received further tuition from [[Sister Mary Leo|Dame Sister Mary Leo]] at St Mary's College Music School.  Sister Mary Leo was internationally recognised as one of the great music teachers, and she later taught another famous New Zealand soprano, Dame [[Kiri Te Kanawa]].\n\n==International recognition==\n\nMajor later moved to England for further study at the London Opera Centre under the guidance of teacher [[Ruth Packer]]. Her successes include winning the 1963 [[Mobil Song Quest|New Zealand Mobil Song Quest]] beating Te Kanawa who placed second (Te Kanawa later won the 1965 contest). She also won the Australian [[Melbourne Sun-Aria]] in 1965, and the London-based [[Kathleen Ferrier Award]] in 1966. Major later performed in international concerts including a [[BBC]] concert broadcast in London, an outdoor concert at the [[Egyptian pyramids|pyramids]] in Egypt with the [[Cairo Opera House|Cairo Symphony Orchestra]], and a charity concert for [[Vera Lynn]] in London. She has performed more than 30 opera roles in their original languages.{{fact|date=September 2019}}\n\nMajor was made a [[Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE)<ref>{{cite web|title=KNIGHTS AND DAMES OF THE ORDERS OF CHIVALRY|url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/nzom3|work=New Zealand Honours Lists|publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet|accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref> in 1991 in recognition of her contributions to music, and a Principal Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit (PCNZM) in the [[2008 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2008 New Year Honours]] for services to opera.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/new-year-honours-list-2008 | title=New Year honours list 2008 |date=31 December 2007 | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet | accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> This was later exchanged for Dame Grand Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/list.asp?id=46 | title=New Zealand Honours Lists | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |year=2008 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Major received the [[Benny Award]] from the [[Variety Artists Club of New Zealand|Variety Artists Club of New Zealand Inc]].\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vacnz.com/bennyaward/|title=Variety Artists Club of NZ Benny Award Recipients|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016033941/http://www.vacnz.com/bennyaward/|archivedate=16 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2008, Major performed a solo and duet with [[Hayley Westenra]] on the ChristChurch Cathedral Choir 2008 UK Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christchurchcathedralchoir.com/ | title=ChristChurch Cathedral Choir 2008 UK Tour | publisher=christchurchcathedralchoir.com |year=2008 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/266275/ART-BEAT | title=With passion | publisher=stuff.co.nz |date=13 February 2008 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> On 18 March 2011, Major performed in the national Christchurch memorial service at [[Hagley Park, Christchurch|Hagley Park]] of [[Christchurch]] in the presence of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]], Prime Minister [[John Key]], [[Bob Parker (mayor)|Bob Parker]], Hayley Westenra, [[ChristChurch Cathedral, Christchurch|ChristChurch Cathedral]] Choir, dignitaries, international rescue teams and tens of thousands of [[New Zealanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/christchurch-memorial-music-performers-march-18-19-29-video-4072141/video | title=Christchurch memorial music performers | publisher=dpmc.govt.nz |date=18 March 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> On 25 February 2012, Major performed with soprano Amina Edris and tenor Chase Douglas in the Waikato Times Hamilton Gardens Arts Festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamiltongardensartsfestival.co.nz/performers/234-1-Countertenors-The-Voice-of-an-Angel |title=Dame Malvina Major \u2013 Coming Home |publisher=dpmc.govt.nz |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/6119956/Dame-Malvina-top-act-for-festival |title=Dame Malvina top act for festival |publisher=stuff.co.nz |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|2012 Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee Honours]], Major was appointed to the [[Order of New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee Honours List 2012 |url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/node/1045 |work=New Zealand Honours Lists |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=29 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604202359/http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/node/1045 |archivedate=4 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This is the highest honour awarded by the Queen of New Zealand, and entitles members of use the post-nominal letters ONZ.\n\n==Education==\n\nMajor is currently{{when|date=August 2015}} Professor of Voice at the [[University of Waikato]] in [[Hamilton, New Zealand]].\n\nIn 1992 she established a foundation to promote education through awards and provide training for young New Zealanders in the performing arts. One such recipient of her personal training is Hayley Westenra.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*  Official website http://www.damemalvinamajorfoundation.org/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Order of New Zealand}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Major, Malvina}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Dames Grand Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Singers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female singers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand music teachers]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand singers]]\n[[