076544|title=Baby Boy \u2013 EP de Beyonc\u00e9 no Apple Music|work=[[iTunes Store]] (BR)|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|date=October 6, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[CD single]]\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Baby-Boy-CD-Beyonce-2003-10-06/dp/B01K8M5G58|title=Baby Boy by Beyonce : Amazon.fr: Musique|website=[[Amazon Music|Amazon.fr]]|date=October 6, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Germany\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.de/Baby-Boy-Beyonce-Knowles/dp/B0000CBI1P|title=Baby Boy \u2013 Beyonce Knowles: Amazon.de: Musik|website=[[Amazon.de]]|date=October 6, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100702/https://www.amazon.de/Baby-Boy-Beyonce-Knowles/dp/B0000CBI1P|archive-date=February 28, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United Kingdom\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Baby-Boy-CD-1-Beyonce/dp/B0000DF4NU|title=Baby Boy [CD 1]: Amazon.co.uk: Music|website=[[Amazon.co.uk]]|date=October 6, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Baby-Boy-CD-2-Beyonce/dp/B0000DF4NV|title=Baby Boy [CD 2]: Amazon.co.uk: Music|website=[[Amazon.co.uk]]|date=October 6, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[12-inch single]]\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Baby-VINYL-Beyonce-Sean-Paul/dp/B0000DF4NW|title=Baby Boy [12\" VINYL]: Amazon.co.uk: Music|website=[[Amazon.co.uk]]|date=October 6, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada\n| October 7, 2003\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Maxi single\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Sony Music\n| align=\"center\"| <ref name=Can/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Germany\n| October 13, 2003\n| align=\"center\"| <ref name=\"Ama.ger\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n| October 14, 2003\n| 12-inch single\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{flatlist|\n* Columbia\n* Music World}}\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Baby-Boy-Vinyl-Beyonce/dp/B0000DG07T|title=Beyonce \u2013 Baby Boy [Vinyl] \u2013 Amazon.com Music|website=[[Amazon Music]]|date=October 14, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 28, 2003\n| CD single\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Baby-Boy-Beyonce/dp/B0000B00JB|title=Beyonce \u2013 Baby Boy \u2013 Amazon.com Music|website=[[Amazon Music]]|date=October 28, 2003|accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|id=8ucz_pm3LX8|title=Official music video}}\n\n{{Beyonc\u00e9 songs}}\n{{Sean Paul}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baby Boy (Beyonce Knowles Song)}}\n[[Category:Beyonc\u00e9 songs]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance/Mix Show Airplay number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Dancehall songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Jake Nava]]\n[[Category:Sean Paul songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Beyonc\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Beyonc\u00e9]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{short description|21st-century Beyonce recorded song}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Baby Boy\n| cover      = Beyonce - Baby Boy (single).png\n| alt        = A woman is standing with her arms open, meanwhile smiling and looking back. She wears a short light-blue shirt, a blue skirt and a rosary on her neck.\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Beyonc\u00e9]] featuring [[Sean Paul]]\n| album      = [[Dangerously in Love]] and [[Dutty Rock]]\n| B-side     = \"[[Summertime (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Summertime]]\" (remix)\n| released   = {{start date|2003|8|3|mf=y}}\n| format     = \n* [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n* [[Compact Disc single|CD]]\n* [[maxi single]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     = {{plain list|\n* [[The Hit Factory]]<br /><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n* South Beach Studios<br /><small>([[Miami]], [[Florida]])<ref name=\"liner\"/></small>}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[dancehall]]\n| length     = 4:04\n| label      =\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Music World Entertainment|Music World]]\n| writer     =\n* Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles\n* [[Scott Storch]]\n* Robert Waller\n* [[Sean Paul|Sean Paul Henriques]]\n* [[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]]\n| producer   =\n* Scott Storch\n* Beyonc\u00e9\n| chronology = [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n| prev_title = [[Fighting Temptation]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Me, Myself and I (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Me, Myself and I]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Sean Paul]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Breathe (Blu Cantrell song)|Breathe]]\n | prev_year  = 2003\n | title      = Baby Boy\n | year       = 2003\n | next_title = [[I'm Still in Love with You (Sean Paul song)|I'm Still in Love with You]]\n | next_year  = 2004\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Baby Boy'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Beyonc\u00e9]] featuring Jamaican [[dancehall]] singer [[Sean Paul]] from Beyonc\u00e9's debut solo [[studio album]] ''[[Dangerously in Love]]'' (2003). Both artists co-wrote the song with [[Scott Storch]], Robert Waller and [[Jay-Z|Shawn \"Jay-Z\" Carter]]; the former also co-produced the song. Containing a lyrical interpolation of \"No Fear\" by [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] group [[Originoo Gunn Clappaz|O.G.C]], \"Baby Boy\" is an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[dancehall]] song with Caribbean and Asian influences; its lyrics detail a woman's fantasies.\n\n[[Columbia Records]] and [[Music World Entertainment]] released \"Baby Boy\" as the second single from ''Dangerously in Love'' on August 3, 2003. \"Baby Boy\" topped the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for nine consecutive weeks and was Beyonc\u00e9's longest-running solo number-one single until 2007, when it was surpassed by \"[[Irreplaceable]]\". It reached the top ten in many countries and was certified platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) and the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). It also reached the top 10 in Australia, Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway, Scotland, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom.\n \nThe song's [[music video]] was directed by [[Jake Nava]] and mostly shows Beyonc\u00e9 dancing in various locations. \"Baby Boy\" has remained a staple of Beyonc\u00e9's concert [[set list]]s. The [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|American Society of Composers, Authors, and Publishers]] (ASCAP) recognized it as one of the most performed songs of 2004. In 2005, American [[singer-songwriter]] Jennifer Armour filed a [[copyright infringement]] lawsuit claiming that the song had used the primary musical [[hook (music)|hook]] from her song \"Got a Little Bit of Love for You\". The suit was later dismissed.\n\n==Background and development==\n[[File:SeanPaul2005.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Sean Paul]] (''pictured'') contributed vocals to \"Baby Boy\".]]\nIn 2002, Beyonc\u00e9 went to [[Miami]], [[Florida]], in the United States, to work with American record producer [[Scott Storch]] for her debut solo studio album ''[[Dangerously in Love]]''.<ref name=\"liner\"/> She and Storch wrote \"Baby Boy\", with contributions from American songwriter Robert Waller and Beyonc\u00e9's now-husband, [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] artist [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"liner\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Dangerously in Love]] |others=Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles |year=2003 |first=Beyonc\u00e9 |last=Knowles |authorlink=Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles |type=Compact Disc Liner Notes|publisher=[[Columbia Records]] |id=5044750 959529 |location= |page=2 }}</ref> The song also contains a lyrical interpolation of \"No Fear\" by hip hop group [[Originoo Gunn Clappaz|O.G.C.]] used towards the ending of the song: \"We steppin' in hotter this year\".<ref name=\"Docu\">{{Cite video |title=Dangerously in Love |publisher=Columbia Records |date=2003}}</ref>\n\nOnce the track was supposedly done, Beyonc\u00e9 had the idea that it would be \"perfect\" if Jamaican [[reggae]] artist [[Sean Paul]] contributed a vocal track.<ref name=\"Docu\"/> Beyonc\u00e9 contacted Paul about a possible collaboration for \"Baby Boy\".<ref name=\"Gil\">{{cite web |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |title=Jigga Who? Beyonc\u00e9 Shares Fantasies With Sean Paul On 'Bonnie & Clyde' Sequel |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1470568/20030314/destinys_child.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV News]].[[MTV Networks]] |date=March 17, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Thread\">{{cite web |author=Thread editors |title=Beyonc\u00e9's debut Album, Dangerously In Love |url=http://www.thread.co.nz/article/554 |work=Thread Magazine |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080122183145/http://www.thread.co.nz/article/554 |archivedate=January 22, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sean Paul agreed, and flew in from Jamaica to join the recording sessions of the song.<ref name=\"Docu\"/> He contributed a [[Deejay (Jamaican)|toast]] verse, and they finished recording \"Baby Boy\" in March 2003, during the later stages of the album's recording.<ref name=\"Gil\"/>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n{{listen\n|filename=BabyBoySample.ogg\n|pos=left\n|title=\"Baby Boy\"\n|description=\"Baby Boy\" is a hybrid of R&B and dancehall with influences of reggae, house and Indian music.\n|format=[[Ogg]]\n}}\n\"Baby Boy\" is a [[Tempo|midtempo]] [[contemporary R&B]] and [[dancehall]] song<ref name=\"Sheetmusicplus\"/><ref name=\"Nichols\">{{cite news |last=Nichols |first=Natalie |date=June 24, 2003 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/24/entertainment/et-nichols24 |title=Review: ''Dangerously in Love''. |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> with [[reggae]], [[house music|house]] and South Asian influences.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gerard |first=Morgan |title=Time is the Master |url=http://www.peacemagazine.com/66/SeanPaul.html |work=[[Peace Magazine]] |publisher=CANDIS publication |accessdate=March 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715060419/http://www.peacemagazine.com/66/SeanPaul.html |archivedate=July 15, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last=Fitzpatrick |first=Rob |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/beyonce/7130 |title=Review: ''Dangerously in Love'' |work=[[NME]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |date=July 2, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-05-27/news/31868952_1_beyonc-freakum-dress-hard-work/2|title=Beyonc\u00e9 rocks Revel: Passion, hard work, and a call for respect|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|page=2|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|first=Dan|last=DeLuca|date=May 27, 2012|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> It was composed using [[Time signature|common time]] in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[C minor]], and set in moderate [[groove (music)|groove]] of 92 [[Tempo|beats per minute]].<ref name=\"Sheetmusicplus\">{{cite web |title=Baby Boy Sheet Music|url=http://www.sheetmusicplus.com/store/smp_inside.html?item=5037527&cart=1210428773&page=01 |publisher=Sheet Music Plus |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> Storch's knowledge on [[Music of India|Indian]] contributes to its [[Music of Asia|Asian]] influences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scott Storch's Outrageous Fortune |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/2 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]] |date=June 29, 2006 |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080418052217/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/2 |archivedate = April 18, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Neil Drumming]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' noted that \"'Baby Boy' goes full-tilt [[Bollywood]] 'n da hood, with Sean Paul ripping a pulsing [[tabla]] [[raga]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Drumming |first=Neil |title=Music Review: Dangerously in Love (2003) |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,459850,00.html |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc]] |date=June 27, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9's vocals are accompanied by clicky and [[castanet]]-sounding [[Beat (music)|beats]],<ref name=\"Times\">{{Cite news |last=Verrico |first=Lisa |title=Beyonc\u00e9: Dangerously in Love&nbsp;\u2013 Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles is growing up, but not too much |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/cd_reviews/article1143631.ece |work=[[The Times]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |date=June 20, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011 | location=London}}</ref> [[Synthesizer|synthesized]] [[Clapping|handclaps]] and [[Slapping (music)|slaps]].<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/l_reviews_a/30050.html|title=Yahoo! Music Album Review: Beyonce&nbsp;\u2013 'Dangerously In Love'|first=James |last=Poletti|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]. [[Yahoo!]]|date=July 7, 2003|accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> According to Roger Friedman of [[Fox News Channel]], \"Baby Boy\" is based on the reggae song \"[[Here Comes the Hotstepper]]\" (1995), performed by Jamaican singer [[Ini Kamoze]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Friedman |first=Roger |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Takes Credit for 'Writing' Songs |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,172552,00.html |publisher=[[Fox Entertainment Group]]. [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] |date=October 18, 2005 |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424225951/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,172552,00.html |archive-date=April 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n\"Baby Boy\" is considered to be a sequel to [[Jay-Z]]'s song \"[['03 Bonnie & Clyde]]\" (2002) featuring Beyonc\u00e9.<ref name=\"Gil\"/> The lyrics detail a woman's fantasies, and in keeping with the album's overall theme, Beyonc\u00e9's deemed them as personal to her.<ref name=\"Thread\"/> Paul remarked: \"She's telling me about her fantasies and picturing me and her going here and there, all over the world&nbsp;... I'm answering back, like, 'I'm wit it'.\"<ref name=\"Gil\"/> The lyrics are constructed in the toast\u2013chorus\u2013verse form; Sean Paul performs the toasting while Beyonc\u00e9 sings all other [[Song structure (popular music)|verses]] and [[refrain|choruses]]. The pattern is repeated twice; a further chorus and verse follow, resolving at the toasting and final verse.<ref name=\"Docu\"/>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Beyonce Baby Boy.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Beyonc\u00e9 singing \"Baby Boy\" during [[The Beyonc\u00e9 Experience]] in 2007, flanked by two dancers|alt=Two men and a woman are looking forward. Both men are wearing military-style clothing, while the woman is holding a microphone. She wears gypsy-style clothing. In the background, many musical instruments are visible.]]\n\"Baby Boy\" was released as the second single from Beyonc\u00e9's debut studio album, ''[[Dangerously in Love]]'' (2003). It was serviced to [[Contemporary hit radio|contemporary hit]] and [[Rhythmic contemporary|rhythmic contemporary radio]] in the United States on August 3, 2003.<ref name=\"rhythmic\">[http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=8/03/2003&Format=9 Rhythmic \u2013 Week Of: August 3, 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715144435/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=8%2F03%2F2003&Format=9 |date=July 15, 2011 }} [[Radio & Records|Radio and Records]]. August 3, 2003. Retrieved February 17, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"pop2\">{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=8/03/2003&Format=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715144441/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=8%2F03%2F2003&Format=1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 15, 2011 |title=Top 40 \u2013 Week Of: August 3, 2003 |publisher=Radio and Records |date=August 3, 2003 |accessdate=February 17, 2011 }}</ref> It was released as a [[CD single]] and [[12-inch single]] in the United Kingdom on October 6, 2003. The song was released for [[maxi single]] in Canada the following day,<ref name=Can>{{cite web |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] (Canada). Amazon Inc |url=https://www.amazon.ca/dp/B0000DB4SJ |title=Baby Boy: Featuring Sean Paul (Maxi) |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> and in Germany on October 13.<ref name=\"Ama.ger\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.de/dp/B0000CBI1Q |title=Baby Boy (Single, Maxi) |language=German |publisher=Amazon.com (Germany). Amazon Inc |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> It was released in the United States as a 12-inch and CD single on October 14 and 28, 2003, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Baby Boy |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0013CPHMA |publisher=Amazon.com (US). Amazon Inc |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> \"Baby Boy\" was included in the revamped edition of Sean Paul's second studio album ''[[Dutty Rock]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite web |title=Dutty Rock (Original recording reissued)|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0000BWVC0 |publisher=Amazon.com (US). Amazon Inc |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2005, American singer\u2013songwriter Jennifer Armour filed a [[copyright infringement]] [[lawsuit]], claiming that Beyonc\u00e9 had used some lyrics and the musical [[hook (music)|hook]] from her song \"Got a Little Bit of Love for You\".<ref name=\"Fox\">{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Suit Over Beyonc\u00e9's 'Baby Boy' Lyrics Goes to Appeals Court |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,299318,00.html |publisher=Fox News Channel. Fox Entertainment Group |date=October 4, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325164454/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,299318,00.html |archive-date=March 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=MTV News staff |title=For The Record: Quick News On Beyonc\u00e9, Britney Spears, Hilary Duff, Snoop, White Stripes, Simon Cowell & More |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1505688/20050713/knowles_beyonce.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=July 13, 2005 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Case\">''Armour v. Knowles'', [[Case citation#Unpublished decisions|No. H-05-2407, 2006 WL 2713787]] ([[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|S.D.Tex.]] September 21, 2006).</ref> In 2003, Armour's former label manager had submitted [[demo (music)|demo recordings]] to [[record label]]s, including Beyonc\u00e9's [[Columbia Records]] and Sean Paul's [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite web |author=MTV News staff |title=For The Record: Quick News On Britney Spears, Beyonc\u00e9, Kristin Cavallari, Beck, T.I., Lil' Kim & More |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1542190/20061003/knowles_beyonce.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=October 3, 2006 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"IE\">{{Cite news |title=Beyonc\u00e9 cleared of copying song |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/beyonce-cleared-of-copying-song-1256857.html |work=[[The Independent]] |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=January 3, 2008 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> According to the district court, an [[expert witness]] (Chair, Department of Music Theory & Composition, [[Shepherd School of Music]], [[Rice University]]) determined the songs to be \"[[substantial similarity|substantially similar]]\" (a requirement for an infringement finding). With regard to the musical hook, the expert witness stated in his report: \"When the aural comparisons of the two songs are presented in the key of [[C minor]] (for easy comparison) and presented back-to-back, in A\u2013B\u2013A\u2013B fashion, even the least musically inclined listener should immediately determine that the two songs are strikingly similar; I daresay that many listeners may even perceive them as being the same song! And again, transposing a song for this purpose does not alter any fundamental qualities or characteristics of the song but merely assists the ability of those unfamiliar with the technicalities of music in making a comparison.\" The district court judge nonetheless ruled that she, herself, couldn't hear the similarities between the two songs and dismissed the case, denying the motion for the songs or case to be heard by a jury.<ref name=\"Case\"/> On appeal, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] affirmed the district court's ruling, but ruled with different reasoning. It held that there was no infringement based on Beyonc\u00e9's claim that Armour's demo tape was received shortly after the writing of Beyonc\u00e9's song had been substantially completed. However, the court did not address the issue of substantial similarity.<ref name=\"IE\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ca5.uscourts.gov/opinions%5Cpub%5C06/06-20934-CV0.wpd.pdf |title=Armour v. Knowles|format=PDF|publisher=[[Case citation#Lower federal courts|512 F.3d 147]] |location=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] |year=2007|accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine reviewer Anthony DeCurtis wrote that Beyonc\u00e9 sounded as if she was \"having fun\" on the song,<ref>{{cite web |last=DeCurtis |first=Anthony |title=Album Reviews: Dangerously In Love |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/beyonce/albums/album/291273/review/6209670/dangerously_in_love |work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media |date=July 10, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071230074103/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/beyonce/albums/album/291273/review/6209670/dangerously_in_love |archivedate = December 30, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> while [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of the online music guide service [[AllMusic]] described Beyonc\u00e9's vocals as \"assured and sexy\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |title=Dangerously in Love > Overview |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=dangerously-in-love-r641728|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[AllMusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923150541/http://www.cmc.dk/ |archivedate=September 23, 2010 |df= }}</ref> [[Mark Anthony Neal]] of the international [[Online magazine|webzine]] [[PopMatters]], regarded \"Baby Boy\" as one of the \"high-profile collaborations\" on ''Dangerously in Love''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Neal |first=Mark Anthony |title=Getting Grown |url= http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/b/beyonce-dangerously.shtml |magazine=[[PopMatters]] |date=July 11, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> Lisa Verrico of the daily British newspaper ''[[The Times]]'' described the song a \"[[Latino (demonym)|Latino]]-tinged collaboration ... Paul does a reggae rap in the middle, but it's when he chats while Beyonc\u00e9 half raps that the pair have real chemistry\".<ref name=\"Times\"/> Yancey Strickler of the ''[[Flak Magazine|Flak]]'' magazine wrote that \"'Baby Boy'<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Diwali Riddim|diwali]] stutter is enhanced by Sean Paul's dancehall monotone\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Strickler |first=Yancey |title=Beyonc\u00e9: Dangerously In Love |url=http://www.flakmag.com/music/beyonce.html |work=[[Flak Magazine]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJames Anthony of the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented that the track \"bridges the gap between the genres of R&B and dancehall\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Anthony |first=James |title='Of course you can lose yourself'  |url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/filmandmusic/story/0,,1852025,00.html |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=August 18, 2006 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' writer Natalie Nichols wrote that \"the ... house-spiced 'Baby Boy' successfully meld[s] [Beyonc\u00e9's] breathy cooing with hip, interesting production.\"<ref name=\"Nichols\"/>\n\n==Accolades==\nBritish record label [[EMI]] was honored by the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP) at the 2005 ASCAP Pop Music Awards as Publisher of the Year for publishing \"Baby Boy\", among other songs.<ref name=\"ASCAP\">{{cite web |title=ASCAP Pop Music Awards 2005 |url=http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/popawards/2005/ |publisher=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> [[Scott Storch]] earned Songwriter of the Year award at the same event.<ref name=\"ASCAP\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Baby Boy\" attained a positioning on the commercial charts before its [[Compact Disc single|physical release]] in the United States. The track led to a higher [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart placing for ''Dangerously in Love'', and helped the album to attain multi-platinum certification in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Stacy-Deanne |author2=Kenyatta, Kelly|author3= Lowery, Natasha |title=Alicia Keys, Ashanti, Beyonc\u00e9, Destiny's Child, Jennifer Lopez & Mya: Divas of the New Millennium |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ZGMcUEvkyEC|publisher=Amber Books Publishing |year=2005 |pages=60\u201361 |isbn=978-0-9749779-6-6 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> The single debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], at number fifty-seven, while its predecessor \"[[Crazy in Love]]\" was still on the top spot.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billboard Hot 100 |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100?chartDate=2003-06-12&order=gainer|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=August 21, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> \"Baby Boy\" dominated the airplays in the United States, ultimately reaching the top of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martens |first=Todd |title=Beyonc\u00e9, Sean Paul Creep Closer To No. 1 |url=http://login.vnuemedia.com/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1977331 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=September 11, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Martens2\">{{cite web |last=Martens |first=Todd |title='Tailfeathers' Still Shakin' Singles Chart |url=http://login.vnuemedia.com/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1969224 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=August 4, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Martens3\">{{cite web |last=Martens |first=Todd |title='Baby' Kicks 'Tailfeather' From Chart Roost |url=http://login.vnuemedia.com/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1986302 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=September 25, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> It reached the chart's top spot eight weeks after its debut, and stayed there for nine consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"Martens3\"/><ref name=\"Martens\">{{cite web |last=Martens |first=Todd |title='Stand Up' Ends 'Baby Boy' Reign |url=http://login.vnuemedia.com/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=2042602 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=November 28, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> The single stayed number one for a week longer than \"Crazy in Love\" had, becoming Beyonc\u00e9's longest-charting number-one single. The feat was not broken until her single \"[[Irreplaceable]]\" (2006), from her second album ''[[B'Day (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|B'Day]]'' (2006), spent ten weeks at the top spot from late 2006 until early 2007 due to heavy airplay.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hasty |first=Katie |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Makes It Ten Weeks At No. 1 With 'Irreplaceable' |url=http://login.vnuemedia.com/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003543450 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=February 8, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> The song became Sean Paul's first number-one single in the United States. \"Baby Boy\" stayed on the Hot&nbsp;100 for twenty-nine weeks,<ref name=\"bbbey\">{{cite web |title=\"Baby Boy\" Global Chart Positions and Trajectories |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=beyonc\u00e9|chart=all}} |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> and was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on June 6, 2006.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web |title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Gold and Platinum |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Beyonce&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151722/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Beyonce&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |archivedate=September 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref> \"Baby Boy\" achieved success on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[crossover (music)|crossover]] and [[mainstream radio]] charts, appearing on the [[Top 40 Tracks]], [[Rhythmic (chart)|Rhythmic]] and [[Mainstream Top 40]], as well as peaking atop the [[Hot 100 Airplay (Radio Songs)|Radio Songs]] and [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]], and at number two on [[Dance Club Songs]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Martens |first=Todd |title=No Stopping Beyonc\u00e9's 'Baby Boy' At No. 1 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/68523/no-stopping-beyonces-baby-boy-at-no-1 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=October 23, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BillChartHis\">{{cite web |title=Beyonc\u00e9: Artist Chart History |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=beyonc\u00e9|chart=all}} |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"AllMusicGuide\">{{cite web |title=Beyonc\u00e9 > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=beyonc-p349078/discography|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Martens2\"/> As of October 6, 2010, \"Baby Boy\" had sold 6,000 physical units in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/66598/week-ending-oct-3-2010-americas-most-popular-inmate |title=Week Ending Oct. 3, 2010: America's Most Popular Inmate |first=Paul |last=Grein |publisher=Yahoo! Music. Yahoo! |date=October 6, 2010 |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, \"Baby Boy\" performed just as well, peaking inside the top ten on all of the charts it appeared on, excluding the [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]], [[Ultratop 50|Ultratop 50 Wallonia]] and [[Italian Singles Chart]],\non which it reached the top twenty. The single debuted at number two in the United Kingdom, becoming the chart's highest debut of the week and \"Baby Boy\"'s highest entry internationally.<ref name=\"uk18\"/> Even though it spent eleven weeks on the chart, it failed to reach the top, being held off by \"[[Where Is the Love?]]\" by [[The Black Eyed Peas]].<ref name=\"uk18\">{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Long%20Time%20Coming |title=The Official Charts Company \u2013 Chart For Week Up To 18/10/2003 |date=October 18, 2003 |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410175556/http://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/LONG%20TIME%20COMING/ |archive-date=April 10, 2015 }}</ref> In Australia and New Zealand, \"Baby Boy\" peaked at numbers three and two, respectively.<ref name=\"aus\">{{cite web |publisher=australian-charts.com. Hung Medien |title= Beyonc\u00e9 Feat. Sean Paul \u2013 Baby Boy (Song)|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Beyonc%E9+feat%2E+Sean+Paul&titel=Baby+Boy&cat=s |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"rianz\">{{cite web |publisher=charts.nz |title= Beyonc\u00e9 Feat. Sean Paul \u2013 Baby Boy (Song)|url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Beyonc%E9+feat%2E+Sean+Paul&titel=Baby+Boy&cat=s |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> It was certified platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for shipments in excess of 70,000 units.<ref name=\"aria\">{{cite web|title=ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2003 Singles |url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2003.htm |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212185621/http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2003.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Baby Boy\" was filmed by English director [[Jake Nava]], who also shot Beyonc\u00e9's \"Crazy in Love\" video. It was recorded in [[Miami|Miami, Florida]] on August 7\u20138, 2003. Parts of the video were captured in a house with different style rooms: one in a Japanese style and one in an old English style.<ref>{{cite web |last=Reid |first=Shaheem |title=Sean Paul Appears In The Flesh In Beyonc\u00e9's 'Baby Boy' Clip |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1477103/20030820/paul_sean.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=August 20, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nScenes featuring Beyonc\u00e9 and Paul are shown separately. The video begins with Paul sitting on a throne while [[Deejay (Jamaican)|toasting]]; Beyonc\u00e9 is leaning against a wall and dancing. In the following scene, Beyonc\u00e9 is seen on a bed. Paul is shown with several women who are lying on the floor caressing each other. Beyonc\u00e9 walks towards the beach; she spots a man, and the two touch and flirt. As the second verse of the begins, Beyonc\u00e9 is at a party. At the party Beyonc\u00e9 decides to dance with the same man that she interacted with earlier. Then, water floods the floor of the party as she sings \"the dance floor becomes the sea\". As the second chorus of the song begins, the video is cut with scenes of Beyonc\u00e9 and four back-up dancers dancing on a platform in the sand on the beach. The original track is interrupted towards the end with an [[Arabic music|Arabic]] instrumental, designed for the music video. This section showcases Beyonc\u00e9 vigorously dancing on the sand.\n\nSal Cinquemani of the online publication [[Slant Magazine]], described the video as a \"baby-oil-logged follow-up\" to \"Crazy in Love\"'s \"bootylicous video\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cinquemani |first=Sal |title=03 Year in Rewind |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/features/2003yearinmusic.asp |magazine=[[Slant Magazine]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> In 2013, John Boone and Jennifer Cady of [[E! Online]] placed the video at number nine on their list of Beyonc\u00e9's ten best music videos, praising the extended belly-dancing breakdown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.eonline.com/news/383554/2013-super-bowl-countdown-beyonc-eacute-s-top-10-music-videos-ever|title=2013 Super Bowl Countdown: Beyonc\u00e9's Top 10 Music Videos Ever!|publisher=[[E! Online]]. [[E!]]|first1=John|last1=Boone|first2=Jennifer|last2=Cady|date=February 1, 2013|accessdate=April 28, 2013}}</ref> \"Baby Boy\" premiered on [[MTV]]'s program ''[[Total Request Live]]'' on August 25, 2003 at number ten and reached the top spot.<ref name=\"TRL\">{{cite web |title=Total Request Live debuts |url=http://host17.hrwebservices.net/~atrl/trlarchive/db.html |publisher=Popfusion |accessdate=February 16, 2011|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080102172613/http://host17.hrwebservices.net/~atrl/trlarchive/db.html |archivedate = January 2, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRL Number Ones |url=http://host17.hrwebservices.net/~atrl/trlarchive/no.html |publisher=Popfusion |accessdate=February 16, 2011|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080415223822/http://host17.hrwebservices.net/~atrl/trlarchive/no.html |archivedate = April 15, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> It stayed on the show for forty-one days, the same chart run \"[[Me, Myself and I (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Me, Myself and I]]\" earned.<ref name=\"TRL\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:Beyonce at Montreal 2013.jpg|thumbnail|250px|Beyonc\u00e9 performing \"Baby Boy\" during [[The Mrs. Carter Show World Tour]] at the [[Bell Centre]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] on July 22, 2013|alt=An image showing five women wearing black outfits in front of a screen]]\nBeyonc\u00e9 first performed \"Baby Boy\" live at the [[2003 MTV Video Music Awards]];<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cinquemani |first=Sal |title=The Kiss(es) Heard 'Round the World: 2003 MTV Music Video Awards |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/features/vma2003.asp |magazine=Slant Magazine |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> she sang it in a [[List of musical medleys|medley]] with the pre-recorded vocals of Paul<!--, and also performed \"Crazy in Love\" with Jay-Z-->.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jay-Z Prevented Sean Paul From Performing With Beyonc\u00e9 At VMAs |url=http://music.yahoo.com/sean-paul/news/jay-z-prevented-sean-paul-from-performing-with-beyonce-at-vmas--12061807 |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]. Yahoo! |date=September 5, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 later sang \"Baby Boy\" with Paul at the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2003|2003 MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Wiederhorn |first=Jon |title=It's Justin's Night As Christina, Kelly Osbourne Fight At MTV Europe Awards |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1480240/11062003/timberlake_justin.jhtml?headlines=true |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate= February 16, 2011}}</ref> \"Baby Boy\" has been included on the [[set list]] for most of Beyonc\u00e9's concert tours. It served as opening song of her [[Dangerously in Love Tour]] (2003). During her performance of the song on the tour, she was initially suspended from the ceiling of the arena that was gradually lowered to a red lounger\u2014a prop she also used during the 2003 MTV Video Music Awards.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Simpson |first=Dave |title=Beyonc\u00e9 |url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/reviews/story/0,,1077421,00.html |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=November 4, 2003 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> The footage taken at [[Wembley Arena]] in [[London]], [[England]] was included on Beyonc\u00e9's first [[live album]] ''[[Beyonc\u00e9: Live at Wembley|Live at Wembley]]'' (2004). Beyonc\u00e9 also performed \"Baby Boy\" with her former group [[Destiny's Child]] during their final tour [[Destiny Fulfilled... and Lovin' It]] (2005), and it was included on their second live album ''[[Destiny's Child: Live in Atlanta]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"incor\">{{cite web |last=Shaheem |first=Reid |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Puts On Flawless \u2013 And Fall-Less \u2013 NYC Show With Robin Thicke |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1566431/20070806/knowles_beyonce.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=October 6, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"Baby Boy\" was a part of Beyonc\u00e9's set list on [[The Beyonc\u00e9 Experience]] (2007) in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], and on [[I Am... World Tour]] (2009\u201310).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuts.co.uk/video/search/all?term=Baby+boy+by+beyonce&x=0&y=0 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724121730/http://www.nuts.co.uk/video/search/all?term=Baby+boy+by+beyonce&x=0&y=0 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 24, 2011 |title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Baby Boy |work=[[Nuts (magazine)|Nuts]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011 }}</ref> On August 5, 2007, Beyonc\u00e9 performed the song at the [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]];<ref name=\"jiv\">{{Cite news |first=Jon |last=Pareles |title=Romance as a Struggle That She Will Win |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/06/arts/music/06beyo.html?ex=1344052800&en=c1ef16024c49370c&ei=5088 |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |date=August 6, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"mui\">{{cite web |first=Shaheem |last=Reid |title=Beyonce Puts On Flawless \u2013 And Fall-Less \u2013 NYC Show With Robin Thicke |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1566431/beyonce-puts-on-flawless-8212-fallless-8212-nyc-show.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=August 7, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> wearing a belly-dancer-type outfit, she descended the staircase holding an umbrella and was met by three men wearing fatigues.<ref name=\"mui\"/> A short section of [[Chaka Demus & Pliers]]' song \"[[Murder She Wrote (song)|Murder She Wrote]]\" (1993) was incorporated into \"Baby Boy\".<ref name=\"mui\"/> Jon Pareles of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the performance, writing that Beyonc\u00e9 \"needs no distractions from her singing, which can be airy or brassy, tearful or vicious, rapid-fire with staccato syllables or sustained in curlicued melismas. But she was in constant motion, strutting in costumes\".<ref name=\"jiv\"/> She performed in a similar arrangement at the Los Angeles' [[Staples Center]] on September 2, 2007. She was dressed in a belly dancing outfit, and the performance was executed with several male backup dancers and live instrumentation.<ref>{{cite video|people=Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles|title=[[The Beyonc\u00e9 Experience Live]]|date=2007|publisher=Columbia Records}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 re-produced the dance she executed in the song's music video.<ref name=\"incor\"/> When Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"Baby Boy\" in [[Sunrise, Florida|Sunrise]], [[Florida]] on June 29, 2009, she was wearing a glittery gold leotard. When her performance began, she was suspended in the air, and then lowered to the [[B-stage]] to where she sang \"Baby Boy\" with an excerpt from [[Dawn Penn]]'s \"[[You Don't Love Me (No, No, No)]]\". Animated graphics of turntables, faders and other club equipment were projected behind the dancers and musicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-record.com/content/2009/06/28/article/beyonce_is_fierce_talent |title=Review: Beyonce is ... Fierce talent |author=Parke Puterbaugh |publisher=New Records |date=June 29, 2009 |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120308121341/http://www.news-record.com/content/2009/06/28/article/beyonce_is_fierce_talent |archivedate=March 8, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 was accompanied by her backing band Suga Mama, which consisted of two drummers, two keyboardists, a percussionist, a horn section, three imposing backup vocalists and the lead guitarist Bibi McGill.<ref name=\"Self\">{{Cite news|accessdate=February 16, 2011|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/23/arts/music/23beyonce.html?_r=1 |title=Flash, Concepts and, Yes, Songs |first=Ben |last=Ratliff|work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=June 22, 2009\n}}</ref> \"Baby Boy\" was included on her live album ''[[The Beyonc\u00e9 Experience Live]]'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/be/album/the-beyonce-experience-live/id268305666 |title=The Beyonc\u00e9 Experience (Live) [Audio Version] |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (Belgium). [[Apple Inc]] |language=Dutch |date=November 19, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> and the deluxe edition of ''[[I Am... World Tour]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/be/album/i-am-world-tour/id399850850 |title=I Am...World Tour |publisher=iTunes Store (Belgium). Apple Inc |language=Dutch |date=November 26, 2010 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> At the 2005 [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP Pop Music Awards]], \"Baby Boy\", along with Beyonc\u00e9's two other singles from ''Dangerously in Love'' \u2013 \"Me, Myself and I\" and \"[[Naughty Girl (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Naughty Girl]]\" \u2013 was recognized as one of the most performed songs of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Most Performed Songs |url=http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/popawards/2005/winners.html |publisher=American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers |accessdate=February 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522212013/http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/popawards/2005/winners.html |archivedate=May 22, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n\"Baby Boy\" was performed by Beyonc\u00e9 in a pink fringe dress at a concert at [[Palais Nikaia|Palais Nika\u00efa]] in [[Nice, France|Nice]], France, on June 20, 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/06/20/beyonce-invades-the-stage-at-european-concert-kickoff-video/ |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Invades The Stage At European Concert Kickoff (Video) |work=[[Rap-Up]] |publisher=Devin Lazerine |date=June 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> and at the [[Glastonbury Festival 2011|Glastonbury Festival]] on June 26, 2011, where she brought out British [[trip hop]] singer [[Tricky (musician)|Tricky]] to guest on the song.<ref name=\"glastonbury2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/57589|title=Beyonce covers Kings Of Leon and Prince at Glastonbury|work=NME |publisher=IPC Media |date=June 27, 2011|accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> Between May 25\u201328, 2012, Beyonc\u00e9 performed the song during her ''[[Revel Presents: Beyonc\u00e9 Live]]'' [[revue]] at [[entertainment]] [[resort]], [[hotel]], [[casino]] and [[spa]] [[Revel Atlantic City|Revel]] in [[Atlantic City]], [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sheridan|first=Emily|title='Feels so good to be back home on stage': Beyonce shows off her post-baby curves as she performs for first time since Blue's birth|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2150267/Beyonce-Atlantic-City-concert-Singer-performs-1st-time-Blues-birth.html|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527083330/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2150267/Beyonce-Atlantic-City-concert-Singer-performs-1st-time-Blues-birth.html|archivedate=May 27, 2012|date=May 26, 2012|accessdate=June 12, 2012|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"spinmag\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/05/run-world-showgirls-beyonce-gets-back-business-atlantic-city/ |title=Run the World (Showgirls): Beyonce Gets Back to Business in Atlantic City |work=Spin |publisher=Spin Media LLC |first=Caryn |last=Ganz |date=May 29, 2012 |accessdate=June 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604070805/https://www.spin.com/2012/05/run-world-showgirls-beyonce-gets-back-business-atlantic-city/ |archivedate=June 4, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"village\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2012/05/beyonce_ovation_revel_may_26_review.php|title=Live: Beyonc\u00e9 Brings The House Down At Atlantic City's Newest Casino|work=The Village Voice|publisher=Village Voice Media|first=Maura|last=Johnston|date=May 27, 2012|accessdate=June 12, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529031543/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2012/05/beyonce_ovation_revel_may_26_review.php|archivedate=May 29, 2012|df=}}</ref> Jim Farber of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' wrote: \"The first, and last parts of the show stressed the steeliest Beyonc\u00e9, told in bold songs... [like] dancehall-inflected 'Baby Boy.'\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-05-26/news/31862521_1_beyonc-obama-group-first-lady-michelle-obama|title=Beyonc\u00e9 matures as she dazzles with depth|work=Daily News|publisher=Daily News L.P|first=Jim|last=Farber|date=May 26, 2012|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> On February 3, 2013, Beyonc\u00e9 performed the song during the [[Super Bowl XLVII halftime show]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/04/sports/football/beyonce-brings-intensity-to-halftime-show-and-silences-doubters.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Silences Doubters With Intensity at Halftime|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|first=Jon|last=Caramanica|date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=April 28, 2013}}</ref> In 2013, Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"Baby Boy\" as a medley with \"[[Get Me Bodied]]\" during her [[The Mrs. Carter Show World Tour]] (2013\u201314), while the songs were performed separately in 2014. The song was also performed during [[The Formation World Tour]] (2016).\n\n==Track listings and formats==\n{{Track listing\n| headline     = \"Baby Boy\"{{nobold|&nbsp;\u2013 12-inch single}}<ref name=\"aus\"/>\n| total_length = {{duration|m=25|s=38}}\n| title1       = Baby Boy\n| note1        = Album version) (featuring [[Sean Paul]]\n| length1      = {{duration|m=4|s=4}}\n| title2       = Baby Boy\n| note2        = [[Junior Vasquez]] Club Anthem Remix) (featuring Sean Paul\n| length2      = {{duration|m=8|s=50}}\